Package com.github.yellowstonegames.text

Class DescriptiveColor

java.lang.Object
com.github.yellowstonegames.text.DescriptiveColor
public final class DescriptiveColor
extends java.lang.Object
A palette of predefined colors as packed IPT ints, and tools for obtaining IPT int colors from a description. An IPT int color isn't especially usable on its own, but you can pass one to toRGBA8888(int) to get an RGBA color as an int (typically used with DigitTools.hex(int) to get a value like FF7F00FF, which in RGBA8888 format is orange). The IPT color space is used here because allows mixing two or more colors very smoothly, without introducing erroneous hues or having dips or ridges in lightness. IPT is a whole complex color space, but most usage is probably going to only need describe(CharSequence), which sidesteps IPT entirely and returns an RGBA8888 int, or maybe some operations on entries in the palette. The aforementioned describe() is used by processColorMarkup(CharSequence), which also takes a color description and translates it to a libGDX-compatible color markup tag. The syntax for color descriptions is in parseDescription(CharSequence); it looks like "lighter rich pink orange", to give an idea of it.
For the palette, you can access colors by their constant name, such as cactus, by the NAMED map using NAMED.get("cactus"), by getting a color by its name's position in alphabetical order with NAMED.getAt(12), or by index in the IntList called LIST. When accessing a color with ObjectIntMap.get(Object), if the name is not found, get() will return TRANSPARENT. If you want to control the not-found value, you can use ObjectIntMap.getOrDefault(Object, int). You can access the names in a specific order with NAMES (which is alphabetical), NAMES_BY_HUE (which is sorted by the hue of the matching color, from red to yellow to blue (with gray around here) to purple to red again), or NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS (which is sorted by the intensity of the matching color, from darkest to lightest). Having a name lets you look up the matching color in NAMED. You can also modify or re-order NAMED if you want to, such as to add more named colors.

    Modifier and Type Method Description
    static int darken​(int s, float change)
    Interpolates from the packed IPT int color s towards black by change.
    static int describe​(java.lang.CharSequence description)
    A quick utility method that calls parseDescription(CharSequence) and then passes that off to toRGBA8888(int), getting an RGBA-format int from a color description.
    static int dullen​(int s, float change)
    Brings the chromatic components of s closer to grayscale by change (desaturating them).
    static int enrich​(int s, float change)
    Pushes the chromatic components of start away from grayscale by change (saturating them).
    static float hue​(int iptColor)
    Gets the hue of the given encoded color, as a float from 0f (inclusive, red and approaching orange if increased) to 1f (exclusive, red and approaching purple if decreased).
    static float lerp​(float fromValue, float toValue, float progress)
    Linearly interpolates between fromValue to toValue on progress position.
    static int lerpIntColors​(int s, int e, float change)
    Interpolates from the packed float color start towards end by change.
    static int lighten​(int s, float change)
    Interpolates from the packed IPT int color s towards white by change.
    static int limitToGamut​(int packed)
    Iteratively checks whether the given IPT color is in-gamut, and either brings the color closer to 50% gray if it isn't in-gamut, or returns it as soon as it is in-gamut.
    static int mix​(int[] colors, int offset, int size)
    Given several colors, this gets an even mix of all colors in equal measure.
    static int parseDescription​(java.lang.CharSequence description)
    Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed IPT int color.
    static int parseDescription​(java.lang.CharSequence description, int start, int length)
    Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed IPT int color.
    static java.lang.String processColorMarkup​(java.lang.CharSequence markupString)
    Processes color markup of the form [|description], where description is in the format that parseDescription(CharSequence) understands (such as "light dullest green cyan"), and changes the markup to a format libGDX can use, [#FF7F00FF].
    static float saturation​(int iptColor)
    Gets the saturation of the given encoded color, as a float ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f, inclusive.
    static int toRGBA8888​(int decoded)
    Converts a packed IPT int color in the format used by constants in this class to an RGBA8888 int.

      public static float hue​(int iptColor)

    • lighten

      public static int lighten​(int s, float change)
      Interpolates from the packed IPT int color s towards white by change. While change should be between 0f (return s as-is) and 1f (return white), s should be a packed color, as from a constant here. This method does not necessarily keep the resulting color in-gamut; after performing some changes with this or other component-editing methods, you may want to call limitToGamut(int) to make sure the color can be rendered correctly.
      Parameters:
      s - the starting color as an IPT int
      change - how much to go from start toward white, as a float between 0 and 1; higher means closer to white
      Returns:
      a packed IPT int that represents a color between start and white
      See Also:
      the counterpart method that darkens a float color

    • enrich

      public static int enrich​(int s, float change)
      Pushes the chromatic components of start away from grayscale by change (saturating them). While change should be between 0f (return start as-is) and 1f (return maximally saturated), start should be a packed color, as from a constant in this class. This usually changes only Cw and Cm, but higher values for change can force the color out of the gamut, which this corrects using limitToGamut(int) (and that can change Y somewhat). If the color stays in-gamut, then Y won't change; alpha never changes.
      Parameters:
      s - the starting color as a packed float
      change - how much to change start to a saturated color, as a float between 0 and 1; higher means a more saturated result
      Returns:
      a packed float that represents a color between start and a saturated color
      See Also:
      the counterpart method that makes a float color less saturated

    • limitToGamut

      public static int limitToGamut​(int packed)
      Iteratively checks whether the given IPT color is in-gamut, and either brings the color closer to 50% gray if it isn't in-gamut, or returns it as soon as it is in-gamut.
      Parameters:
      packed - a packed IPT int color; often this color is not in-gamut
      Returns:
      the first color this finds that is between the given IPT color and 50% gray, and is in-gamut

    • parseDescription

      public static int parseDescription​(java.lang.CharSequence description)
      Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed IPT int color. Color descriptions consist of one or more lower-case words, separated by non-alphabetical characters (typically spaces and/or hyphens). Any word that is the name of a color in this palette will be looked up in NAMED and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name words, the colors will be mixed using mix(int[], int, int), or if there is just one color name word, then the corresponding color will be used. The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the intensity of the described color; likewise, "rich" and "dull" change the saturation (the difference of the chromatic channels from grayscale). All of these adjectives can have "-er" or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. If a color name or adjective is invalid, it is considered the same as adding the color TRANSPARENT.
      Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve", and "lightest richer apricot-olive".
      This overload will check the first character of description and may change how it parses depending on that char. If the first char is #, and there are 6 characters remaining, this parses those 6 characters as a hex color in RGB888 format. If the first char is # and there are 8 or more characters remaining, it parses 8 of those characters as an RGBA8888 hex color. If the first char is |, that char is ignored and the rest of the CharSequence is treated as a color description (this is to ease parsing markup for processColorMarkup(CharSequence)). Otherwise, the whole CharSequence is parsed as a color description.
      Parameters:
      description - a color description, as a lower-case String matching the above format, or a #-prefixed hex color
      Returns:
      a packed IPT int color as described

    • parseDescription

      public static int parseDescription​(java.lang.CharSequence description, int start, int length)
      Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed IPT int color. Color descriptions consist of one or more lower-case words, separated by non-alphabetical characters (typically spaces and/or hyphens). Any word that is the name of a color in this palette will be looked up in NAMED and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name words, the colors will be mixed using mix(int[], int, int), or if there is just one color name word, then the corresponding color will be used. The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the intensity of the described color; likewise, "rich" and "dull" change the saturation (the difference of the chromatic channels from grayscale). All of these adjectives can have "-er" or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. If a color name or adjective is invalid, it is considered the same as adding the color TRANSPARENT.
      Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve", and "lightest richer apricot-olive".
      This overload always considers its input a color description, and won't parse hex colors.
      Parameters:
      description - a color description, as a lower-case String matching the above format
      start - the first character of the description to read from
      length - how much of description to attempt to parse
      Returns:
      a packed IPT int color as described

    • describe

      public static int describe​(java.lang.CharSequence description)
      A quick utility method that calls parseDescription(CharSequence) and then passes that off to toRGBA8888(int), getting an RGBA-format int from a color description.
      Parameters:
      description - a color description, as a lower-case String matching the format in parseDescription(CharSequence)
      Returns:
      an RGBA8888-format int matching the described color
      See Also:
      the syntax for color descriptions is here

    • processColorMarkup

      public static java.lang.String processColorMarkup​(java.lang.CharSequence markupString)
      Processes color markup of the form [|description], where description is in the format that parseDescription(CharSequence) understands (such as "light dullest green cyan"), and changes the markup to a format libGDX can use, [#FF7F00FF]. The only addition this makes to libGDX markup is the [| starting character combination, which here marks a color description rather than a named color from libGDX's Colors class (which are all upper-case, so they wouldn't conflict anyway).
      Parameters:
      markupString - a CharSequence, most commonly a String, that may contain color markup starting with [|
      Returns:
      a String that has the [| markup changed to libGDX-compatible [#
